Unfortunately, today is not that tone of many meetings and the promise of a “more compassionate, more compassionate” policy has long been forgotten if it ever really began to be implemented.
It is increasingly evident that different views are not tolerated in the Labour Party and that each opinion is judged on the basis of whether it is acceptable to the party leadership.
This started shortly after Jeremy became leader, as colleagues with whom I had previously considered that we had similar political views began to expect me to turn 180 degrees and adopt EU views that I would never agree with, whether they were about national security or not.
Every time I spoke in public, no matter what I was actually saying, I heard a buzz on social media, where some people were calling for my rejection, they denounced the center’s policy and told me I shouldn’t be a member of the Labour Party.
And that didn't just happen to me.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than my other colleagues, as the comments addressed to me were usually political.
I admire the professionalism and determination of my colleagues who face a flurry of sexist or racist insults every day, but they never back down.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era in politics is how insults are now considered regularity.
Jeremy Corbyn claimed last week that the Labour Party should encourage a culture of tolerance. . . .
The reality is that we are no longer a broad faction and that with every proposal of denial or change of the rules of choice, the party’s boundaries narrow.
I have been advised many times over the last two years not to raise my voice, not to talk too much and that "everything will be okay".
But I didn't go into politics to do that.
Since I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago, as a student still, due to the neglect shown by the Thatcher government which literally led to the failure of my entire class, my purpose has been to defend better public services for those who need them most, either as a member of the government.
I never hid my politics, and I did the same in the last election.
No one in the Nottingham East could have been confused in any way as to my political views and points of disagreement with today’s leadership.
To those who put forward the objection on Friday, all I have to say is that while the country is facing a Brexit that will hurt our households, businesses and public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on whether I am loyal to the leader of the Labour Party.
But, really, my only message is not to the members of the Momentum movement in Nottingham, but to my constituents, whether they are members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise you that it is not a threat of rejection or political expediency.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
