"The sea is ours": Bolivia hopes that the court will once again open the way to the Pacific
Marines patrol the fully-equipped naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings, blue flags are waving.
On the naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon is written the slogan: "Our sea is rightfully ours.
It’s our job to get her back.”
Throughout landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the coastline that Chile conquered after a bloody conflict over the exploitation of natural resources in the 19th century is still alive, as is the longing of its people to travel.
These hopes have risen today more than ever, for decades, as Bolivia awaits the International Court of Justice’s ruling on October 1 after five years of consultation.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and tranquility, and of course expects the result with a positive eye,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the International Court of Justice’s ruling on big screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will decide in favor of Bolivia’s claim to have a court in Chile, after decades of turbulent talks, to negotiate.
Evo Morales, the charismatic indigenous president of Bolivia, who is waging a controversial battle for re-election next year, has much to gain or lose from Monday’s decision.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to decide in favor of Bolivia and that, even if it did, they would not change much.
The UN body in the Netherlands does not have the power to give away Chilean lands and has made it clear that it will not determine the outcome of possible discussions.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s ruling is due to be issued just six months after the submission of the final arguments suggests that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zarate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And instead of furthering Bolivia’s goals, the past four years may have undermined them.
“Today’s Bolivian government has raised the issue of access to the sea,” Zarate said.
Morales’ aggressive rhetoric has exhausted any remaining good mood in Chile, he argued.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold discussions after that.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Velje, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making process was unusually fast.
On Monday, Bolivia will have "an excellent opportunity to usher in a new era of relations with Chile" and the opportunity to "end 139-year disagreements with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who remains one of Latin America's most popular leaders, is using the issue of going to the sea as a political crusade.
“Bolivia will never renounce its right to access the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
The decision is an opportunity to see that we must overcome the past.”
