John Edwards: Language Skills are Necessary for the Citizens of the World
Scotland’s independent schools have a history of academic excellence, which continued in 2018, with yet another series of outstanding exam results, which were only further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other community approaches.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, which are represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible level of service to students and their parents.
The goal of independent schools is to prepare their students for the next and higher educational levels, the professional career they will choose, and their position as citizens of the world.
As an educational field that can design and implement a custom school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable course of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to someone in a language they understand, then what you say comes into their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, what you say comes into his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s exams, we find that languages are at the top of the scoreboards, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a bachelor’s degree of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 per cent of students achieved an A-degree in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of those who studied German, 69 per cent of those who studied French and 63 per cent of those who did not.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed by children and young people in the future.
Languages today, as a course of choice, are considered as important as courses related to science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Committee found that, in terms of the reasons why employers struggled to fill vacancies, a 17 per cent share was due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, the need to acquire language skills is becoming increasingly urgent, so that young people are prepared for their future professional careers.
Since more future employment opportunities require language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future, due to this skill that you will be able to use throughout your life.
If one is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, then automatically this multilingual person will have an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to make a conversation, while French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of respondents (15 percent).
For this reason, investing in language teaching today is important for today's children.
Knowledge of many languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will give children better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered more important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child is interested in, there will always be some languages to choose from in independent schools, which have specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scotland’s independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
There is no denying today that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be extremely important for the future of the country, so this reality should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, multiculturalism and excellence for Scotland’s youth.
They have to do it.
John Edward is the Director of the Councils of Independent Schools of Scotland.
